In relation to RQ1, full regression results, including 95\% Confidence Intervals, are shown in @tbl-rq1-results. This model was significant ($F(1, 3368)=380.1, p <.001)$, and results indicated that age was a significant predictor of FoMO $(\beta = -0.2, CI_{95} = [-0.22, -0.18], SE = 0.01, p <.001)$. Age explained approximately 10% of the variance in FoMO scores. For every one-year increase in age, participants' FoMO scores decreased by 0.20 points. This suggested that older participants experienced less FoMO than younger participants (see @fig-rq1(a)).


